Part I, Homography

Homography, or perspective rectification, is the process of adjusting a 2D image from one perspective to another (e.g. taking an image tha appears at a slant with vanishing perspectiv points and transfroming it to an image that appears head on). For examples of this in action, see:

  • learnopencv.com/homography-examples-using-opencv-python-c/
  • inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs194-26/fa17/upload/files/proj6A/cs194-26-adp/
  • people.scs.carleton.ca/~roth/comp4900d-12/notes/homography.pdf (pages 17-22)

Python has built in code that will find the transformation matrix for this linear operator.

For this project you will take or find an image taken from a slanted angle, and use the tools below to straighten it out so it looks like its taken head on.

Instructions

  1. Write code in the cell below that uses the points you found in problem 3 to determine the homography matrix, and applies this matrix to transform the image. See the code at the bottom of this file for an example.
In[]:
src_points = np.array([[60, 90], [220, 60], [220, 250], [58, 220]])

# Define the coordinates of the rectangle in the transformed image (head-on view)
# Adjusted to match the corners of the slanted image
dst_points = np.array([[90, 100], [75, 185], [270, 225], [230, 90]])

# Calculate the homography matrix using the points
homography_matrix, _ = cv2.findHomography(src_points, dst_points)
print(f"Homography Matrix = {homography_matrix}")

# Transform the image by the homography matrix
fixed_math_image = transform.warp(np.array(math_image), homography_matrix)

# Swap width and height of the transformed image
fixed_math_image = np.swapaxes(fixed_math_image, 0, 1)

# Display the transformed image
plt.imshow(fixed_math_image, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
plt.show()

Part II, Homogenous Coordinates

Homogeneous coordinates allow us to realize translations - things like $T(\vec{v})=\vec{v}+\vec{v}_0$, which you know are not linear transformations - as linear transfromations in a higher dimension. Pretty cool, especially given how simple they are. Humans are so smart! Amazing.

Instructions

  1. Read Section 6.5 of your text on homogenous coordinates and graphics.
  2. Using homogeneous coordinates find a matrix that rotates vectors in $\mathbb{R}^2$ by 30 degrees clockwise, then scales the image such that $<x,y>$ becomes $<2x,7y>$, and then translates the image by the vector $\vec{v}=< 50, 20 >.$
  3. Encode the matrix you found in problem 2 below and use it to transform your image.
In[]:
theta = np.radians(math.pi/6)  # Rotation angle in radians (clockwise)
rotation_matrix = np.array([[np.cos(theta), -np.sin(theta)],
                            [np.sin(theta), np.cos(theta)]])

# Define the scaling matrix to scale the image such that <x, y> becomes <2x, 7y>
scaling_matrix = np.array([[2, 0],
                            [0, 7]])

# Define the translation vector to translate the image by the vector <50, 20>
translation_vector = np.array([50, 20])

# Combine the rotation and scaling matrices
rotation_scaling_matrix = np.dot(rotation_matrix, scaling_matrix)

# Define the transformation matrix
transformation_matrix = np.eye(3)  # Identity matrix
transformation_matrix[:2, :2] = rotation_scaling_matrix
transformation_matrix[:2, 2] = translation_vector

# Apply the transformation to the image
transformed_image = transform.warp(np.array(math_image), transformation_matrix)

# Display the transformed image
plt.imshow(transformed_image, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
plt.show()

We learned how linear algebra can be used to make homographic photos and how more general aspects of linear algebra can be applied (especially with coding). Part I's homography was enjoyable with changing the image to make it look like you were facing it head-on. It was a bit daunting at first because on paper, it sounds like an absolute nightmare to code, but working through it piece by piece made it manageable. The most challenging part was definitely Part II. Understanding how we were supposed to code the transformation was difficult and there was a lot of trial and error with getting the image to not be a stretched-out mess.
